To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment;

to identify critical processes and functions; 

to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 

to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 

to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Require all officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances immediately;
Exert all efforts to expedite liquidation of cash advances of officers and employees who have already died or are no longer in service. After exhausting efforts to have these accounts settled and no other alternative procedures are available, management may file a request for write-off for accounts which were considered dormant and identities of the same could no longer be determined;
Exert all efforts to expedite liquidation of cash advances of officers and employees who have resigned or no longer in service;
Submit the Schedule of Dormant Accounts quarterly on or before the 15th day of the ensuing month;
Record the liquidation of cash advances for confidential funds granted in 
CYs 2015-2018 supported with the duly received copy of the transmittal letter of its liquidation in accordance with Section 6.2.2.4 of the COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 dated January 8, 2015; and
Consider the preparation of a request for write-off of the Receivable accounts which were considered dormant pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008.
We would like to emphasize that the Circular shall not be interpreted to condone the accounts written-off nor to extinguish the obligations. The Management shall continue to exert effort to collect the accounts appearing in the Registry of Accounts Written-Off (Annex 10) or Registry of Derecognized Dormant Accounts (Annex 11) when circumstances warrant. Further, this shall not be construed as a ground to exonerate from liability the officers/employees for infidelity in the custody of documents.

Recommendations:
We recommended that management strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of the PPE account of the Municipality, specifically, the following:
Local Chief Executive:
To temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee from all their regular duties to be able to complete the physical inventory of all PPEs of the LGU in due time;
Direct the Property Unit, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, to prepare a PIP containing at least the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;
The Inventory Committee:
Conduct a complete physical count of PPE based on the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Ensure that the physical count is recorded/documented daily in a standard Inventory Count Form (ICF), using the format in Annex A of this Circular, which shall be used as the basis in the preparation of the RPCPPE after the physical count;
Prepare and submit the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) covering all the PPEs of the LGU;
Prepare and update Property records based on the results of the physical inventory and reconciled with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the LGU's PPEs;
Property and Accounting Unit
The Property and Accounting Units to undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled. The reconciliation to be completed within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee.

